close_symbols: error-code macros returned/used by OS_CHECK_POINTER (e.g. OS_INVALID_POINTER)
explanation:
For checking MISRA C rule "Controlling expressions shall not be invariant" we must inspect any control statements that occur by macro expansion or in called functions. Explanations: 
- OS_CHECK_POINTER: This macro is invoked twice in the function; its expansion may contain conditional/loop controlling expressions (e.g. if (ptr == NULL) ... or asserts). You must inspect its definition to determine whether any controlling expression is invariant. 
- OS_ObjectIdFindByName: The function call is the only non-macro statement that may contain conditional or loop constructs. Its implementation must be inspected for invariant controlling expressions. 
- LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE: This constant/enum is passed into OS_ObjectIdFindByName and could appear in controlling expressions (switch/case, comparisons) inside that function; you need its definition/value. 
- OS_ObjectIdGetByName and OS_ObjectIdRelease: These are direct callees of OS_ObjectIdFindByName (per the call graph). To fully analyze the control expressions inside OS_ObjectIdFindByName you need the implementations of its callees. 
- OS_printf: Commonly used by macros like OS_CHECK_POINTER for diagnostics; its invocation site may be part of a conditional in the macro expansion. Inspecting it helps understand side-effects of the macro. 
- UtAssert_Abort: Assertion helper sometimes invoked by pointer-check macros; if present in the macro expansion it may affect the control flow and needs inspection. 
- osal_id_t: The pointer type checked by OS_CHECK_POINTER — its definition could affect how the pointer check is written (e.g. special sentinel values) and whether any comparisons are invariant. 
- NULL: The canonical null pointer constant used by pointer checks; include to verify whether macros compare against a compile-time constant (which could make a controlling expression invariant). 
- error-code macros returned/used by OS_CHECK_POINTER (e.g. OS_INVALID_POINTER): The macro may return or branch on specific error codes; their definitions/constants help determine if the macro contains invariant expressions or constant-condition branches.

Provide these symbols/definitions to the next analysis agent so it can expand macros and inspect called functions to determine whether any controlling expression within the expanded code is an invariant (and whether any permitted exceptions apply).
